The body wall is very different on each side. On the right side it is relatively tough and bears numerous, closely spaced, parallel transverse muscles extending from the base of the oral siphon to the posterior extremity of the body (
Fig. 3A
). The right side of the body can be rather easily separated from the tunic except along the dorsal and ventral lines.

The body wall tissue contains dense refracting cells (
Fig. 4C
).
